Use **responsive design** with CSS:

- **Flexible layouts:** use `%`, `vw`, `vh`, `rem`, `em`, `flex`, and `grid` instead of fixed pixels.
- **Media queries:** apply different styles at different screen widths.
- **Responsive images/media:** set `max-width: 100%` and `height: auto`.
- **Viewport meta tag:** add this in `<head>` for mobile scaling:
  ```html
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  ```

Example:
```css
/* Base styles */
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  gap: 1rem;
}

/* Tablets */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}

/* Phones */
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  body {
    font-size: 14px;
  }
}
```

This lets the page adapt to smaller screens by stacking content, resizing text, or changing spacing.

Use **responsive design** with CSS:

- **Flexible layouts:** use `%`, `rem`, `vw`, `vh`, `flex`, and `grid` instead of fixed pixels.
- **Media queries:** apply different styles at different screen widths.
- **Responsive images/media:** set `max-width: 100%` and `height: auto`.
- **Mobile-first:** write base styles for small screens, then add larger-screen rules.

Example:

```css
/* Base styles for mobile */
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 1rem;
}

img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}

/* Tablet and up */
@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    flex-direction: row;
  }
}

/* Desktop and up */
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}
```

Also add this in your HTML `<head>`:

```html
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
```

This makes the page scale correctly on mobile devices.

